An evalutation of Fighters in the UFC

Collaborators: Mason Paradise and Conor Syme

Introduction

This tutorial aims to explore the complete data science lifecycle, delving into the intricacies of statistical analysis to uncover insights within the realm of UFC (Ultimate Fighting Championship) fighters. As aficionados of the sport, we are intrigued by the factors that contribute to the success of certain fighters over others, as well as the potential trends prevalent across different weight classes. With the UFC standing as the pinnacle of mixed martial arts (MMA) globally, boasting a rich history since its inception in 1993, our journey through the data science process will illuminate the evolution of this highly regulated, multi-billion dollar enterprise. From its humble beginnings as a showcase of diverse fighting styles to its current status as a platform for the world's premier athletes, the UFC encompasses a myriad of disciplines including Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu, wrestling, Muay Thai, and boxing, offering a fertile ground for statistical exploration. Through meticulous analysis, we seek to unravel the underlying relationships and trends embedded within the data, shedding light on the nuanced factors that shape the success trajectories of UFC fighters across various weight divisions. By leveraging statistical techniques, we aspire to provide actionable insights that not only deepen our understanding of the sport but also contribute to the ongoing discourse surrounding MMA competition.

In this tutorial we will be going through the different parts of the data science lifecycle

  1. Data Collection
  2. Data processing
  3. Exploratory Data Anaylsis (EDA) & Data Visualization
  4. Model: Analysis, Hypothesis testing, & Machine Learning
  5. Interpretation: Insight & Policy Decision

1. Data Collection

In the data collection phase of the data science lifecycle, we have to find a dataset. We were able to find a dataset that we could use to perfrom the analysis from kaggle. The dataset is called UFC Fighters' Statistics 2024 and it has information on 4111 different fighters who have once fought for the UFC as recently as this year. It has 18 columns of information including height, weight, fighting stance, and many other striking and takedown statistics.

For this tutorial and analysis, the programming language we will be using is Python. The tools will be using are Jupyter Notebook and many different APIs such as Pandas, NumPy, and matplotlib. These tools will be used to create the tutorial as well as easily provide information on all of the different data provided.

The next thing we need to do is turn the date_of_birth column into a column for the age of each fighter. Having a column for age will be easier to understand than having a column for when each fighter was born.

To get a column for age, we need to first change the object type in the date_of_birth column into datetime. From that we can get the year for each fighter and subtract that from 2024 to get each fighters age. Once we have the age column, we can delete the date_of_birth column and move the age column to where date_of_birth was.

In[10]:
df['date_of_birth'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date_of_birth'])
df['age'] = 2024 - df['date_of_birth'].dt.year

Now that the height, weight, and reach are converted to US system of units. We want to create a column for the weightclass of each fighter. The UFC currently has 9 different weight classes. These weight classes are Strawweight (115 lbs), Flyweight (125 lbs), Bantamweight (135 lbs), Featherweight (145 lbs), Lightweight (155 lbs), Welterweight (170 lbs), Middleweight (185 lbs), Light Heavyweight (205 lbs), and Heavyweight (265 lbs). The first 4 weight classes cover women's weight classes, and men's is flyweight and above. For some fighters, their weights are 0.01 above a certain weight class so we had to make sure that those fighters were assigned to the right weight class.

In[15]:
weight_classes = {'Strawweight':115,
'Flyweight':125,
'Bantamweight':	135,
'Featherweight': 145,
'Lightweight':155,
'Welterweight':170,
'Middleweight':	185,
'Light heavyweight':205,
'Heavyweight':265}

def assign_weight_class(weight):
    for weight_class,upperlimit in weight_classes.items():
        if weight <= upperlimit or weight == upperlimit + 0.01:
            return weight_class
    return 'Heavyweight'

df['weight_class'] = df['weight_lb'].apply(assign_weight_class)
tmp_col = df.pop('weight_class')
df.insert(10, 'weight_class', tmp_col)

df.head()

3. Exploratory Data Anaylsis (EDA) & Data Visualization

In this section of the tutorial, we are going to take a look at the data to understand its key characteristics and uncover insights. We are going to use many different statisical and visualization techniques to find patterns, identify outliers or anomalies, and form hypotheses within the data. We will be using many different graphs and charts which will help to present the data in a visually inuative manner. This will aid in the identification in different trends, relationships, and outliers to help us give a more informed analysis of the data.

We are now going to take a look at the relationship between height and weight for each fighter. First, we what to get an idea of the amount of the fighters there are in each weight class.

Key factors in determining who the best fighters in the UFC are, is striking, takedowns, and submissions. There are many different styles of fighters. Some may be strikers while others may dominate the ground game with takedowns and submissions. What we are going to do is try and see if there are any patterns or trends within these attributes that will lead to a greater win percentage.

To help display these statistics we are going to use a pairplot. This pairplot is going to compare striking, striking defense, and win percentage. First, we are going to make a striking attribute which multiplies the significant_strikes_landed_per_minute with significant_striking_accuracy / 100. We also need to make a striking defense attribute which multiplies significant_strikes_absorbed_per_minute with significant_strike_defence / 100. These scores will give us an idea of how effective each fighter is at striking and defending. A higher attack score means that the fighter is better at striking and a higher defense score that the fighter takes a lot of hits, so a lower defense score is better.

In[]:
df_strike = df.copy(deep=True)
df_strike = df_strike.loc[(df_strike['significant_strikes_landed_per_minute'] != 0.0) & (df_strike['significant_striking_accuracy'] != 0.0)
                      & (df_strike['significant_strikes_absorbed_per_minute'] != 0.0) & (df_strike['significant_strike_defence'] != 0.0)]
df_strike['striking_score'] = df_strike['significant_strikes_landed_per_minute'] * (df_strike['significant_striking_accuracy'] / 100)
df_strike['striking_defense'] = df_strike['significant_strikes_absorbed_per_minute'] * (df_strike['significant_strike_defence'] / 100)
df_strike = df_strike[['striking_score','striking_defense','win_percentage']]
sns.pairplot(df_strike, height=10);
plt.show()

From looking at the pairplot, most of the fighters have an attack stat less than four. For all of those fighters there really is no relationship with win percentage. However, for the fighters with an attack stat higher than four, most of them a high win percentage. For defense, most fighters have a low defense score so it is difficult to tell whether there is a relationship, but there is something I did notice. Majority of the fighters with a 100% win percentage have a defense score less than 2.5 and all have a defense score less than five. This means that all of the fighters who have not lost yet have a very strong striking defense.

While there may not be much relationship between striking and win percentage maybe there is a relationship between takedowns and win percentage. The higher the takedown score and defense means that the fighter is better at taking people down and defending against takedowns. The takedown score is

In[25]:
array = np.array(y_pred)
actual = y_test.values
squared_error = (actual.astype(float) - array) ** 2
mse = np.mean(squared_error)

print("Mean Squared Error:", mse)

Mean Squared Error: 126.63504333921126

As seen the mean squared error is quite large. In order to address this we will use RANSAC regression in order to improve the predictions. We decided to do this becuase RANSAC distinguishes between inliers and outliers in order to reduce bias.

In[26]:
ransac = RANSACRegressor(LinearRegression(), random_state=42)
ransac.fit(x_clean, y_clean)
inlier_mask = ransac.inlier_mask_
outlier_mask = np.logical_not(inlier_mask)

x_inliers = x_clean[inlier_mask]
y_inliers = y_clean[inlier_mask]

x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x_inliers, y_inliers, test_size=0.05, random_state=42)

model = LinearRegression()

model.fit(x_train, y_train)

y_pred = model.predict(x_test)

for pred, actual in zip(y_pred, y_test):
    print("Predicted: {:.2f}, Actual: {:.2f}".format(pred, actual))
